THE LIQUOR LAWS. On the vote for $7,100 for adminis­tration of Liquor License considerable discussion ensued especially about in­

spectors. Mr. Hajultain said no one knew better than he did that the system was not

satisfactory. fhe difficulty, was to know just what should be done.

it was easy to theorise, but difficult to but theories in to practice. Last year §. had an idea ºf changing the whole system, and called for the co-operation ºf the N.W.M.P. The presence of a

oice officer was always a check upon violations of the law. He knew per­fectly well that for some years after the introduction of the licensing sys­iºn, the N.W.M.P. were under the im­pression that they were relieved from all responsibility. , in regard to carrying out that law. It was a sºrt of re-action from the duties they had had to perform under the old

rohibition law. It was easy to see his from the official reports made by the head officer. Now, the N.W.M. P. were responsible for the carrying out of the law, and particulary of the Territorial rdinances. In consequence of the , official re­ports he interviewed Commis; Sioner Herchmer late last year, and

ing a high tribute

issued a general order that it was the duty of the police to enforce the licens­ing law. With that as a basis he (Mr. Haultain) thought it would be easy to start out, and appoint a few good men to administer the law. Unfortunately at the very beginning the contingent for South Africa was formed and vir­tually broke up the police. He was therefore obliged to abandon, his scheme for a time; but as soon as there were again sufficient policemen at the various points he purposed recommend­ing an entire change in the system of inspection. He proposed to do away to a large extent with the inspectors who were not receiving a sufficient salary to enable them to do very much. At present the inspectors were paid for the actual work, and had also a small retaining fee to ensure a certain amount of interest in the carrying out of the law. Under this system a large amount was paid and nothing was got in return. Then again the public were not very strongly in favor of helping to carry out the law. One of the western Senators had told him that at a prohibition meeting of thirty persons in reply to questions put by him to the meeting, all the 30 voted in favor of prohibition; 27 had taken of a glass recently ; but when they were asked how many would be willing to help to carry out a prohibition law, not one held up his hand. Also when the Temperance party in Regina sub­mitted a series of questions on the sub­ject all over this country, there was a general consensus of opinion adverse to persons doing anything to help to carry out the law, believing that it was the ãº of the Government to do this and not private citizens. Both votes were then agreed to.

THE PUBLIC ACCOUNTs.

Dr. Patrick moved, seconded by Mr. B. Prince, that the following report of the sessional committee on public accounts be concurred in :

The Standing committee on public accounts beg to report that they have examined the public accounts for 1899, making especial enquiry respecting such items as appeared in the opinion of any member of the committee to require explanation and have found such items correct.

The committee has also had under consideration the question of audit and the form in which the accounts have been published and beg to recommend:

1. That the regulations providing for a living allowance of $3.50 per diem to employees of the Government during their absence from the offices on public duty, be amended so as to provide that whén living expenses exceed $1.50 per diem, vouchers for such expenses be required.

2. That when public works, of any kind have been döne by day, labor the amount received, by the foreman in charge of the work and the rate paid him per diem be shown separate from the amount received by laborers work­ing under him.

3. That there should be shown for each year a separate statement of the annount expended in respect of every work or service for which an approp­riation has been inade, the amount expended under warrant in respect of any such work or service, and lapsed balances.—Carried.

CAVALRY HORSEs.

Mr. Bulyea moved that whereas the pastoral industry, especially in its re­iation to the breeding of horses, is one of great importance to the future pros­perity of the Territories, but in this latter particular is one that in the past has not been properly appreciated owing to unstable and erratic market conditions; . And whereas recent events have clearly demonstrated that it is probable there will be an almost nnlinited de­mand for horses, particularly of the type suitable for military purposes as mounted rifle remounts: And whereas the Territories, have been proved to be entinently adapted for the production of every class of horses; And whereas such adaptability in this respect has not been taken ad­vantage of on account of the demand for horses being limited and local : And whereas it has been amply demonstrated by the class of horses

House. Mr. Horace Greeley seconded. Mr. A. S. Rosenroll asked what a re­mount station was. Mr. Bulyea replied that he had had Some correspondence with General Hutton on the subject. A remount station was an establishment or depot where horses could be taken and brok­en to a certain extent. The Imperial Government did not require them to be thoroughly broken. The horses had simply to be tractable and halter broken, and broken to ride. The home authorities would rather do the final training themselves, by their own officers, . They stipulated that the horses should not be bronchos. Mr. A. E. Cross—Who stands the expense of all this? Mr. Bulyea said that would be a mat­ter of detail. He did not think they should try to dictate to the federal authorities. If they took up the mem­orial, and he believed they would take it up, then the federal authorities would stand the expense.

The motion was agreed to unanim­ously.

Mr. Ross said he wished to rise to a question of privilege. It was not often that a member of that House had to rise on such a question. and it was not usual for him to take much notice of newspaper criticisms , or newspaper remarks. However, in the Telegram he was reported as having pointed his finger at the leader of the opposition and said “I will fix you, and get even with you "; and the words were in inverted commas, thus purporting to be the exact words used. He need only say that he did not make use of any such words, nor had he had any intention of making any such remark, or to lead the House to believe he had any such intention. He had simply to say it was an untrue report, and he wished to put himself right with the public. There was no occasion to do so with the House, as the members them­selves heard the speech. Mr. D. H. McDonald said he was only too glad that the hon, member had risen to take exception to the impres­sion that had been conveyed. The stock industry was one of permanent interest to the people of the Territories, and was capable of developing to an unlimited extent. It was a good time to take up the ques­tion owing to the demand for horses that at present existed, and must in­crease for some time. Such horses as were required for military remounts could be produced in the North-West as well, if not better, than in any other country. The horses sent to Africa with the contingents proved this. Representatives from , the Imperial Government had at times been sent over to Canada to report on the sub­ject, but the result had not been very encouraging; not that the horses could not be found, but that there was no system by which the agents could be brought in contact with the horse breeders. If the federal authorities could be induced to take such steps as were indicated in the resolution that would be a good thing. Another reason was that the people of this country had no knowledge of the type of horses that could be raised here. In the West some horse breeders had gone out of the business because they could find no market for their horses, and they had, therefore, gone into the cattle business, in which there was always a sure and certain market. No matter if they raised one hundred or one thou­sand they knew they could have a ready sale. . If they had an assurance of a ready sale for horses they would go into that more profitable trade. If they could raise horses they could sell for from $120 to $125, they would go largely into that class of stock, and have a more profitable business than they were at present engaged in. IN COMMITTEE.

The House then went into committee of the whole, when the following bills passed through; a bill to amend the Ordinance respecting mortgages and sales of personal property; a bill to incorporate Edmonton public hospital; a bill respecting Clerks and deputy Clerks; a bill respecting Sheriffs and deputy Sheriffs; a bill to amend the Pound Ordinance; a bill to grant further powers to the town of Leth­bridge: a bill to amend the Ordinance to add a certain area to the municipal­ity of Indian Head.

VILLAGES.

In committee on the Villages bill, at­tention was called to the taxation of the creameries, Mr. Ross saying that in some towns they were exempt. Mr. A. S. Rosenroll moved that creameries operated by the govern­ment should be exempt. There would be a large number of creameries in the North-West, and they ought to be exempt. The farmers put their hands into their pockets to keep them going and it was hard to have to pay taxes. Mr. Ross said the creameries operated by the Government should be exempt; except when the Government charged up the taxes against the patrons as running expenses. Dr. Elliott said it would not be wise to exempt creameries in villages when they were not exempt in towns. Mr. R. S. Lake pointed out that though the creameries were taxed and the Dominion Government paid the taxes, yet it was made ultimately a charge against the patrons. The matter dropped. Mr. Ross said he proposed to intro­duce an amendment, to make clear how long the | for the election of over­seers could be kept open. In one case a poll was kept open until midnight. He proposed that the time of voting should be extended fifteen minutes and if no votes were polled in that time then it would be closed. I)r. Patrick thought that those who held lands or leases should have a vote, but that mere squatters should not. Mr. R. S. Lake asked why, if the Commissioner appointed all overseer he should not have to give a bond, the same as if he had been elected? Mr. Hoss said that when a man was appointed they could not make him give a bond, of course the Commission­er assumed the responsibility by appointing him. Mr. It. S. Lake suggested that in assessing a village they should have the option of adopting the school assessment where practicable. Mr. Ross said it was as well to do with as few cross references as possible but he would consider the suggestion. On the clause referring to protested

THE PRES13 YTERIAN CHURCH BILL.

Dr. Patrick thought the bill ought to limit the amount of land property the church could hold. There was no limit in the bill and he did not think that wise. They had had experience in re­gard to the Mormon church, and he did not find that the Methodist church or any other church had power to hold an unlimited quantity of land.

Mr. Boss said he did not think a limit was necessary when a church was not exempt from taxation. . . But they had to pay taxes and he could not see the benefit in not allowing them as much as they wanted. There was a point in regard to the length of time they could hold unused lands. The bill said twenty years, but it had been suggested that ten years would be enough. He suggested that progress be reported to enable him to consider the suggestions.

THE AGRICULTURAL SOCIETIES ORDI­NANCE.

Mr. Horace Greeley moved that wher: a society was fifty miles away from any other society it should not be called upon to help with others to make up the sum of $350 before a grant towards an exhibition could be obtain­ed. The present law which would come into operation next year, Placed the small societies in a very bad posi­tion. They would be practically shut down, and would lose what little pro­perty they had. He therefore moved that in case a society whose chief place of business was 50 miles from any other society unless the amount donated be $150 (instead of $350,) there shall be no grant, I}r. Fºlliott said that the Indian Head exhibition last year was not a success as as agricultural exhibition, but as for races and entertainments it was. There were plenty cf M.L.A.'s there, but they were in the grand stand wat: ching the sports, and the ground where the exhibits were was so deserted that, there was an uninterrupted view all round of what there was to be seen. Some of the smaller societies that the present law would kill were far more successful than the one at Indian Head, and did far more to encourage agriculture and the breeding of pure stock. Mr. G. W. Brown pointed out that if they had societies fifty, miles apart it really meant twenty-five, as they would meet at a halfway point. That distance he admitted, was far enough, but it was not too far. Mr. A. S. Rosenroll suggested that the distance should be forty miles. Captain Meyers said that in his dis­trict there was a small society, laboring undergreat disadvantages. The diš. tance between it and Prince Albert was too great for them to co-operate or amalgamate. The little society was too far away to use the railway and at times the roads were impassible. He hoped the amendment of the hon. member from Medicince Hat would ass. The little society he refered to had four acres of land, good buildings and was in every way a successful society ; and if the annendment did not pass it would be killed. Mr. Bulyea said he thought that to pass the amendment would be a ret­rograde movement. He differed from the member for Wolseley in his esti­mate of the Indian Head exhibtion last year. It was a summer exhibition, and therefore it was not possible to have such a good show of that year's §". as could be got in the fall. Indeed they had to exhibit the products of the previous year. There was, however, a good show of implements and ºther matters of use to farmers, while the collection of noxious weeds sent by the North-West Government was an object lesson of great value. In regard to entertain­ments he would say that those that run the shows did not expect the at­tractions to be the chief end of the exhibitions. But it might as well be at once admitted that unless attractions were provided an exhibition could not be made a financial success. There were only four societies affected by the amendment, and he would be glad to put the figure at $200 instead of $350. Mr. A. E. Cross said that in the older provinces they had gone in for larger shows and had made them successes. Here, if the first year of amalgamation was not a success, that was no criterion they would not ultimately be good. The large societies were the successful societies. The amendment was then agreed to, the figure being $200. TEIE PROVIDENT TRUST AND INVEST. MENT Co.
